  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony in the United States and in many other jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This is typically done by passing the money through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions.\n\nIn the U.S., money laundering is primarily prosecuted under federal law, particularly under the Money Laundering Control Act of 1986, which is codified at 18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including substantial fines and imprisonment for up to 20 years per offense, depending on the specifics of the case. Additionally, there may be civil penalties and the forfeiture of assets involved in the laundering scheme.\n\nIt's important to note that even if you are not the one who originally obtained the money illegally, you can still be charged with money laundering if you knowingly engage in financial transactions with the proceeds of criminal activity.\n\nAlways consult with a legal professional if you need advice on this or related matters, as legal consequences can vary widely based on the specifics of each case.",
